<br>
You seemed confused by the status and treatment of the prisoners in Gitmo but if you would bother to read the entire Convention (or at least the part about POW treatment and &quot;unlawful&quot; combatants) you would see that we are in fact abiding by the GC, if not actually being more lenient than required.<br>
<br>
Well since this quote of yours helped start this argument lets go back to the beginning and pick it apart.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>The geneva convention as we know it now didn't exist in WWII. At that time it was even less defined and harder to enforce, much less follow, than it is today which in most aspects is pretty damn hard. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
The Geneva Convention of '49 is a revision of an older document.  The first version came into being in 1864 (though the US was not a party to the treaty at that time.)  There have been 3 revisions since, the last of which was 1949.   There were very few changes made between the 1929 version and the 1949 version.  The Nuremburg trial  and the Japaneses war crime trials were based largely on the 1929 treaty, so they WERE enforced prior to current one (as a side note, we applied the treaty standards to Japan even though they never signed on to the treaty)<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>It only applies to undersigned countries, so by not being representatives of any country al qaeda is not protected by it, and since the taliban government never undersigned it neither are they.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
AQ is not considered a party as far as the convention is concearned they could not &quot;sign&quot; it or even acceded to it if they wanted to.  AQ falls under Article 3 more than anything(though such non-state international entities were not really considered by the convention) and as long as the country they are operating in is a signatory or has acceded to the convention, they have all the protections aforded in Article 3.  But they are also almost to a man, unlawful combatants, which means they forfiet any protection the GC would otherwise offer.  Unless there is a uniformed unit of AQ out there somewhere, very few if any AQ members would be eligible for POW status.<br>
<br>
The Taliban is more clearly covered by Article 3.  Afganistan was a signatory of the Convention.  Does not matter who is actually in charge.  A change in government does not change treaty obligations.   We did not invade, we backed one side of a civil war.  Taliban soldiers, if they could be clearly identified as such, ARE eligible for the more limited protections offered under Article 3.<br>
<br>
And lastly, just what part of the GC don't you think we should abide by?  Seriously, the only thing the GC requires is that non-combatants, (wounded, prisoners, medical personal etc.)  Be treated humanely and with due process.   Just what is your problem with that? <p><center><font face="lucida handwriting, arial" color="006800" size=+2><b>Radgen Waldjaeger</font></b><br><font face="tempus sans ITC, arial" color="675f00" size=+1><b>Semi-retired Pathfinder of Karana</font><br><font face="tempus sans ITC, arial" color="blue" size=+1>Shining Path</font></b><br><img src=http://radgen.homestead.com/files/tiger_run_md_clr.gif></center>
