<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><br>
Although one of the Powers in conflict may not be a party to the present Convention, the Powers who are parties thereto shall remain bound by it in their mutual relations. They shall furthermore be bound by the Convention in relation to the said Power, if the latter accepts and applies the provisions thereof.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
No where in there, does it say that a signatory of the GC can ignore the GC in the event that a non-signatory or even another signatory ignores the GC.<br>
<br>
There is absolutely no statement within the GC where it states that a country can ignore the GC.  Even dealing with Terrorists, and the fighting in Afghanistan, the GC can't be &quot;ignored&quot;.  Terrorists are covered by the GC, they just don't possess the &quot;rights&quot; of a lawful combatant.<br>
<br>
As far as historical examples, I gave them, while you have not.<br>
<br>
WWII - Japan had NOT signed the GC.  They also did not abide by the GC.  The US on the other hand was a signatory and HAD to abide by the GC, even when dealing with Japanesse prisoners.<br>
<br>
Radgen brought up Serbia vs Bosnia.  Again, another conflict where one side had signed the GC, while they other hadn't.  During the conflict both sides ignored the GC.  Now, after the conflict, Serbia is on the chopping block.<br>
<br>
But you on the other hand, can't present ONE instance where a signatory has been in a conflict with a non-signatory that did not abide by the GC, where the signatory then also ignored the GC.  Not a single one.  I'm not even asking for a situation involving the US.<br>
<br>
Any signatory.  Just one Maxa.<br>
<br>
The GC isn't just a treaty between the signing countries.  It's an agreement on how each country will wage war, no matter who they are fighting.  There is never an instance where a signing country can ignore the GC, even when you talk of unlawful combatants.  Though they don't have the same rights as lawful combatants, they still have rights under the GC, which can't be ignored.  We could not use an AQ terrorist as a human land-mine detector, without violating the GC (and a host of other agreements).<br>
<br>
<br>
Just what part of....<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><br>
The High Contracting Parties undertake to respect and to ensure respect for the present Convention in all circumstances.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
is so difficult for you to grasp and understand?  It's the FIRST article of the treaty.  With that article stated, and for you to be right, there would have to be a specific article that states when the GC is not applicable. <p><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=6094" target="top">Wenin Huirunda</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
&quot;You can believe whatever you wish. Just realize that you are wrong. Even if you don't realize it you are still wrong. The end.&quot; - Wise Man</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#4D4D4D><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/bthetribunaldotorg.showUserPublicProfile?gid=maxamaji>MaxaMaji</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/globalWhite.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>I read boards more<br>than I play EQ....</span><br>  Posts: 632<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(11/22/02 3:42:03 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub101.ezboard.com/fthetribunaldotorgfrm36.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=266.topic&index=46>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Grats me on my longest post ever.</span><hr size=1> Good lord where to start. I'll start with this since the general theme seems to be that you're having a hard time deciphering a legal document.<br>
<br>
-Maybe this will help clear it up. Straight and to the point, from General Article 4.<br>
<br>
&quot;Nationals of a State which is not bound by the Convention are not protected by it. Nationals of a neutral State who find themselves in the territory of a belligerent State, and nationals of a co-belligerent State, shall not be regarded as protected persons while the State of which they are nationals has normal diplomatic representation in the State in whose hands they are.&quot;<br>
<br>
Answering Radgen first, since you seem to be able to carry on a legitimate debate with some basis behind it.<br>
<br>
The US has *no* interpretation that we are bound by the GC when fighting entities not bound by the GC. The articles do not leave it open to interpretation. Like I said before, even if we for some reason did interpret it that way, it would be in the US regulations. If it's in the US regulations and that's what you're basing that statement from, then surely you can point to where it is. The answer is it doesn't exist, the US follows the GC by the letter when fighting signatory governments and only then, and it's not a true statement. If you can come up with that documentation, then I'll buy it hook line and sinker. Good first place to look would be FM 100.3 since it's our basic warfighting manual, but I can guarantee you it's not there. The GC is not in any way a &quot;guideline to fighting war&quot;, its a treaty just like any other, between governments. That's why governments that don't agree to it aren't protected under it, as it says in the general articles.<br>
<br>
I'm pretty familiar with whats going on in GTMO. I've been there 6 times since before they moved xray from behind Villamar housing to where it is now, and will be there again in December. If anyone else here has been there feel free to ask me a few questions about that base only someone who's been there a lot would know. We were not, in fact, abiding by the GC in two areas, the housing and the transportation. Open-air chain link cells do not abide by the letter of the GC, however for the area they're living in they're far better than anything we could construct for them other than air-conditioned cells, which isn't happening. When they were being transported, a lot of the prisoners fought, spit, pissed on, and threw shit at the guards, therefore by their own actions causing us to have to put them in the gloves, masks, and shackles. I have over time probably read most of the GC, not all of it for sure but most of the applicable parts. Maybe you have too, but the problem you're having isn't reading it's comprehension.<br>
<br>
Regardless of what it says in Art. 4, do you know why there's that paragraph at the end of Art. 2? If article one meant all circumstances regardless of hell or high water, and not all circumstances between the participant entities (which is what it does mean), then why would there be a reason to put that last statement in art. 2? The reason is that you are grossly misunderstanding article one the same way Wenin is, but what it refers to is fighting between participant nations. When theres a nonparticipant involved, we have article 2 and 4.<br>
<br>
Yes, 1949 was the last major revision to the GC, congrats. But to say there were very few changes between 1929 and 1949 is a gross misconception. I'm not sure what your point is in this paragraph really. Yes, just like I've been saying all along, we did abide by it with Japan for the most part in WWII. We did, but we didn't have to. You're intermixing &quot;enforced&quot; and &quot;abided by&quot; which are two wholly different things, and is what we are arguing about. You're saying we have to (i.e. enforced) and im saying we don't have to but do anyway (i.e. abided by, but not enforced) so your statement in that paragraph isn't clear at all.<br>
<br>
The first sentence regarding AQ is repeating exactly what I said in the quote above it, so no clue where you're coming from again. Another gross misconception you're having is the &quot;acceded to&quot; part. There is no differentiation between &quot;undersigned&quot; and &quot;acceded to&quot;. In order to &quot;accede to&quot; it, they have to provide a signed document acceding to it, which is the same method all signatories use unless they actually want to send their president to Switzerland. Again, government doesn't operate on word of mouth, it operates on having someones ass to hang if they don't do what they signed onto. Either they sign the GC and are protected by it, or the don't and aren't.<br>
<br>
Another misconception- &quot;Afghanistan signed onto it so they're protected, doesn't matter who's in charge&quot;. I have news for you, goverments are held responsible for their adherence to it, not tracts of land. When the taliban came into power in afghanistan they flatly declined being protected by the GC, and therefore the taliban troops are not protected by it. A change in government changes all treaty obligations because the new government is under no obligation to follow the policies of the one it replaced, and the taliban was the new effective government of afghanistan at the time. Changing the old governments policies is typically why new governments come into power. <br>
<br>
<br>
The last paragraph is from deep space. If you could point out anywhere I said that I don't believe we should follow the GC, then I'll gladly explain, but good luck. <br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
Wenin, play the victim if you'd like but insults go both ways. I give you a lot of shit because you absolutely refuse to provide any reasoning to anything you say yet sling insults worse than about anyone. <br>
<br>
Good lord man, are you reading these posts? I've posted TWO specific articles that delineate what is to happen with nonparticipating countries. Both say that nonparticipants are SOL unless they become participants. One you either can't understand or don't want to, and the other I hope you can.<br>
<br>
WWII. Ok, how is that applicable. We abided by it and they didn't, true true. In what way does that further your argument that we *had* to other than just once again you saying *because we had to* in the midst of it? We did because, and once again im repeating myself for the Nth time, it's our policy to. Not because we're bound by the GC to.<br>
<br>
Serbia. Applicable how? Serbia is *on the chopping block* for international war crimes. International war crimes can be commited by anyone of any nation completely regardless of participation in the GC or any other treaty.<br>
<br>
Even though it had nothing to do with the argument, I'll give you a damn good example of a signatory that didn't abide by the GC, which would be the US in Vietnam. Sure we did for the most part, but not by the letter even remotely and have been called out for it repeatedly, just like we're being called out for gtmo. I'll even give you a specific one. One of the articles concerning actual combatants concerns what weapons can be used and what can't. One instance, put in in 1949, dictates what caliber direct fire tube weapon can be used against personnel, if I remember right its .45 cal or it's mm equivalent. The .50 BMG falls outside that parameter because it blows people to chunks and is considered a cruel weapon. Our answer to that was the Quad 50, which is 4 .50 cal machine guns mounted coaxially on the back of a halftrack to get the rate of fire up enough to make it decent for anti-personnel use, which it's not even designed for. We used that for most of the latter half of the war and raised a middle finger at everyone who bitched about it.<br>
<br>
I gave you the proof that we don't have to, and just did again. It's right there in the General Articles that govern the use of the entire document. Now, if you would *kindly* provide some kind of proof that *has to do with the actual discussion we're having* that would rock! <br>
